        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent. | Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Ap. 29<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1880</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I thank you for your very kind note &amp; for sending me the interesting case of inheritance, which I have been glad to see, though it is not likely that I shall again write on the subject<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>Dear Sir | Yours faithfully | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Garrison’s letter has not been found; the case of inheritance has not been identified. CD had collected reports of cases of inheritance of acquired characters when he was working on <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7951.xml"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi></ref>, <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref>, and <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2400.xml"><hi rend="italic">Expression</hi></ref>.</note>
        </div>
    
